  "opinion": "As a fitness trainer in Kansas City who's spent time volunteering with underrepresented groups, I've seen firsthand how stereotype threat can silently sabotage potential in STEM. Stereotype threat isn't just a theory—it's the mental load of knowing you're the 'odd one out' in a room full of people who don't look like you. For instance, when I worked with a group of high school students from immigrant backgrounds, some would avoid math problems because they believed they couldn't succeed, even when their skills were solid. This isn't about innate ability; it's about the fear of confirming a stereotype that's been passed down through generations. In my part-time job, I've noticed how much energy people waste on self-doubt instead of learning. The answer? We need to address it head-on by normalizing diverse voices in STEM classrooms and workplaces. Start with simple, actionable steps: mentorship programs that pair students with role models who look like them, inclusive language in curricula, and creating safe spaces where mistakes are seen as growth opportunities. It's not about changing who people are—it's about changing the narrative around who they can be. I've seen this work in my yoga classes, where people feel more confident when they're encouraged to try new things without fear of judgment. In STEM, we need that same kind of support—structured, intentional, and accessible to everyone. The goal isn't to erase stereotypes but to build bridges so that every student feels they belong in the room.",
